        "Dalio’s model combines several measures of national power: education, innovation, competitiveness, trade, military strength, financial markets, debt, reserve-currency use, and internal order. No single measure explains rise or decline. The framework encourages readers to look for interactions. Education and infrastructure can support productivity; productivity can strengthen trade and currency demand; financial success can expand borrowing; excessive borrowing and inequality can later weaken political cooperation. The sequence is a model, not a schedule.",
